We mourn the loss of the great Japanese writer, Yuko Tsushima (1947-2016), whose writing was &ldquo;as potent and heady as a dry martini&rdquo; (The Village Voice), and return to her wonderful, unnerving story, &ldquo;The Shooting Gallery&rdquo;, translated by Geraldine Harcourt.
The two children suddenly leaned halfway out of the window of the moving train and shrieked in turn:
&lsquo;Look! Over there!&rsquo;
&lsquo;It&rsquo;s all shiny!&rsquo;
&lsquo;Is that the sea?&rsquo;
&lsquo;Watch out or you&rsquo;ll get your heads knocked off!

Presented with a minimum of commentary, Anne Carson’s Antigonick.
We posted a preview back in January, but now have in our possession the only pair of finished copies in the Western Hemisphere (the remainder are being shipped, via freighter, from the speciality printer in China and will arrive in early May). An illustration on translucent velum, with the text visible beneath. I’ve been fond of the term &ldquo;ghosting through.&rdquo;
I love this page.
